<Layout title="Troy Ounces vs Regular Ounces: Gold Weight Explained" description="Understand the difference between troy ounces and regular ounces for gold and precious metals. Learn why jewellers use a different weight system." keywords="troy ounce, gold weight, troy vs regular ounce, precious metals weight, gold ounce, troy ounce to grams, jewellery weight">
  <div class="max-w-3xl">
    <article class="prose dark:prose-invert prose-gray max-w-none">
      <nav class="text-sm text-gray-400 mb-6 not-prose">
        <a href="/blog" class="hover:text-amber-600">Blog</a> <span class="mx-1">›</span> <span class="text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-300">Weight</span>
      </nav>
      <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900 dark:text-white mb-2">Troy Ounces vs Regular Ounces: Gold Weight Explained</h1>
      <p class="text-sm text-gray-400 mb-8">June 11, 2025 • 4 min read</p>

      <p>When you see gold priced at "$2,300 per ounce," that is not the same ounce you use to measure flour in the kitchen. Gold and other precious metals are weighed using troy ounces — a system that dates back to medieval trading. Here is what you need to know.</p>

      <h2>Troy Ounce vs Regular (Avoirdupois) Ounce</h2>
      <div class="bg-amber-50 dark:bg-amber-900/20 border border-amber-200 dark:border-amber-800 rounded-xl p-5 my-6 not-prose">
        <p class="text-center text-lg font-mono font-bold text-amber-700 dark:text-amber-400">1 troy ounce = 31.1035 grams</p>
        <p class="text-center text-lg font-mono font-bold text-amber-700 dark:text-amber-400 mt-1">1 regular ounce = 28.3495 grams</p>
        <p class="text-center text-sm text-gray-500 dark:text-gray-400 mt-2">A troy ounce is about 10% heavier than a regular ounce</p>
      </div>

      <h2>Key Differences</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Weight per ounce:</strong> Troy ounce (31.1 g) is heavier than a regular ounce (28.35 g)</li>
        <li><strong>Ounces per pound:</strong> Troy pound = 12 troy ounces, regular pound = 16 regular ounces</li>
        <li><strong>Pound comparison:</strong> 1 troy pound (373.2 g) is lighter than 1 regular pound (453.6 g)</li>
        <li><strong>Usage:</strong> Troy for precious metals, regular for everything else</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Why Does Gold Use a Different System?</h2>
      <p>The troy system takes its name from Troyes, a town in France that was a major medieval trading hub. Merchants there established standard weights for precious metals and gemstones in the Middle Ages. The system persisted because:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>The international bullion market standardised on troy ounces centuries ago</li>
        <li>Changing would require repricing every gold contract worldwide</li>
        <li>Financial regulators and mints (US Mint, Royal Mint) define coins in troy ounces</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Practical Conversions for Investors</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>1 troy ounce = 31.1035 g</li>
        <li>1 troy ounce = 1.097 regular ounces</li>
        <li>1 kg of gold = 32.15 troy ounces</li>
        <li>Standard gold bar (London Good Delivery) = 400 troy ounces = 12.44 kg</li>
        <li>Gold coin (1 oz) = 31.1 g of pure gold</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Other Precious Metal Units</h2>
      <p>Beyond troy ounces, you may encounter these units in jewellery:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Pennyweight (dwt):</strong> 1/20 of a troy ounce = 1.555 g (used by jewellers for small pieces)</li>
        <li><strong>Grain:</strong> 1/480 of a troy ounce = 0.0648 g (used for very precise measurements)</li>
        <li><strong>Carat (mass):</strong> 0.2 g (used for gemstones, not to be confused with gold karat purity)</li>
      </ul>

      <p>Whether you are investing in gold bars, buying a wedding ring, or checking current spot prices, understanding the troy ounce ensures you know exactly what you are paying for.</p>

      <div class="border-t border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-800 mt-10 pt-8 not-prose">
